t Score of 18/18, Receives AV-Test Verification for the Third Consecutive Time', 'https://www.ttbinternetsecurity.com/news/ttb-antivirus-achieves-perfect-score-of-18-18-receives-av-test-verification-for-the-third-consecutive-time', 'TTB Antivirus', 'TTB Antivirus once again proved its mettle by securing a perfect score of 18/18 in the recent AV-Test evaluation. Download TTB Antivirus for your Android Devices and start protecting them now!', 1, '2023-11-02 09:12:20'),
(30, 'What are expected cybersecurity tips for Black Friday and Cyber Monday in 2023?', 'what-are-expected-cybersecurity-tips-for-black-friday-and-cyber-monday-in-2023', 1, '2131857622black friday news.jpg', '<p>As the holiday season approaches and the allure of Black Friday and Thanksgiving deals intensifies, the internet becomes a breeding ground for cyber threats preying on unsuspecting online shoppers. Therefore, it is very crucial to be vigilant and informed about potential hazards that could compromise your personal information and financial security. This article aims to shed light on the types of cyber threats that tend to surge during the holiday season, particularly during the shopping frenzy of Black Friday and Thanksgiving.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Potential Threats to Your Digital Safety</h2>\r\n\r\n<h3 style=\"color:#434343; font-style:normal\">1. Phishing Scams</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Phishing remains a prevalent and effective method employed by cybercriminals to trick users into revealing sensitive information. During the holiday season, phishing scams often take the form of enticing offers and deals sent via email, SMS, or social media. These deceptive messages may appear to be from well-known retailers, complete with enticing discounts and promotions. To protect yourself, always verify the legitimacy of the sender and refrain from clicking on suspicious links.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3 style=\"color:#434343; font-style:normal\">2. Fake Websites and Apps</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Cybercriminals create counterfeit websites and mobile applications that mimic popular online stores. These fraudulent platforms may look convincing at first glance, with logos, product images, and checkout processes designed to imitate the real deal. Be cautious and only shop from reputable websites and official app stores to avoid falling victim to these deceptive schemes.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3 style=\"color:#434343; font-style:normal\">3. Malicious Advertisements</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Online ads can be a breeding ground for malware, especially during the holiday season when the volume of ads increases. Cybercriminals may inject malicious code into online ads, leading users to compromised websites or triggering malware downloads. Ad-blockers and cautious clicking can mitigate the risks associated with malicious advertisements.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3 style=\"color:#434343; font-style:normal\">4. Public Wi-Fi Risks</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Shopping on the go is convenient but can expose you to security risks, especially when using public Wi-Fi networks. Cybercriminals can exploit vulnerabilities in these networks to intercept your sensitive information. If possible, use a virtual private network (VPN) to encrypt your connection and protect your data when shopping in public places.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3 style=\"color:#434343; font-style:normal\">5. Card Skimming and Payment Fraud</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Be wary of card skimming devices, both online and in physical stores. Cybercriminals may deploy skimming software on compromised websites or install physical skimming devices on point-of-sale terminals. Regularly monitor your bank statements for any unauthorized transactions, and consider using secure payment methods, such as credit cards with fraud protection.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Cybersecurity Measures to Adhere to</h2>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<h3 style=\"color:#434343; font-style:normal\">Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA)</h3>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Enable MFA wherever possible, especially on your online shopping accounts. This adds an additional layer of security by requiring a secondary form of verification, such as a text message or authentication app, along with your password.</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<h3 style=\"color:#434343; font-style:normal\">Regularly Update Software and Devices</h3>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Keep your operating system, antivirus software, and browsers up to date. Cybercriminals often target outdated software to exploit vulnerabilities. Regular updates ensure that you have the latest security patches installed.</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<h3 style=\"color:#434343; font-style:normal\">Beware of Unusual Requests</h3>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Legitimate online retailers will never ask for sensitive information like passwords or credit card details via email. If you receive such requests, consider them red flags and report them immediately. Verify the legitimacy of the request by contacting the retailer directly through official channels.</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<h3 style=\"color:#434343; font-style:normal\">Check Website Security</h3>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Before making a purchase, ensure the website is secure. Look for &quot;https://&quot; in the URL and a padlock symbol in the address bar. These indicate that the website encrypts your data during transmission, making it more difficult for cybercriminals to intercept.</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<h3 style=\"color:#434343; font-style:normal\">Monitor Your Credit Report</h3>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Regularly check your credit report for any suspicious activities. This can help you detect unauthorized access to your accounts or identity theft early on. Many credit reporting agencies offer free credit reports annually.</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<h3 style=\"color:#434343; font-style:normal\">Educate Yourself and Stay Informed</h3>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Knowledge is a powerful defence. Stay informed about the latest cyber threats and scams circulating during the holiday season. Cybersecurity organizations and retailers often release advisories and updates to keep consumers aware of potential risks.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>The Final Word</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>As you gear up for the holiday shopping spree, it&#39;s crucial to arm yourself with knowledge and adopt proactive measures to safeguard your online shopping experience. By incorporating these proactive measures into your online shopping routine, you not only reduce the risk of falling victim to cyber threats but also contribute to a more secure online environment for everyone. Remember, an informed and cautious approach is your best ally in the digital realm, ensuring a happy and secure holiday shopping experience.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 'Thanksgiving and Black Friday Sale', 'what-are-expected-cybersecurity-tips-for-black-friday-and-cyber-monday-in-2023', 'Black Friday , Thanksgiving , Cyber Monday', 'Stay vigilant this Black Friday! With the shopping frenzy in full swing, be aware of potential cyber threats. Protect yourself from cyberattacks and online scams with these security tips.', 1, '2023-11-23 09:57:58'),
(31, 'FEAM Aero Suffers Data Breach Due to LockBit Ransomware Attack', 'feam-aero-suffers-data-breach-due-to-lockbit-ransomware-attack', 1, '1169566001news post  32.jpg', '<p>FEAM Aero, a prominent global aircraft maintenance &amp; technical services provider company, has been targeted by the scandalous LockBit ransomware gang. As a result, the attack has led to the compromise of a considerable amount of sensitive customer and partner data. The Russian-linked hacker collective claims this attack and posted concerning disclosure on its dark leak site, alarming the entire aviation industry.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Reportedly, the hackers have accessed a vast amount of sensitive information from FEAM Aero&#39;s systems and have threatened to leak portions of the cache data within the next 48 hours. LockBit, known for cyber intrusions, has disclosed that they have been able to exploit several vulnerabilities in FEAM&#39;s network infrastructure, obtaining 67 files as proof.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><strong>Sensitive Data Leaked</strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p>The LockBit ransomware group claims that they have access to several sensitive documents files as below:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Partner &amp; Customer Engineering Projects</li>\r\n	<li>Banking and Financial Records</li>\r\n	<li>Insurance Information of Customers &amp; Partners</li>\r\n	<li>NDA and Confidential Contracts</li>\r\n	<li>Secret Drawings and Documents</li>\r\n	<li>Information About the Business Processes</li>\r\n	<li>Internal Management &amp; Company Correspondence</li>\r\n	<li>Databases</li>\r\n	<li>HR Documents</li>\r\n	<li>Engineering System Baselines</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>The extent of the data breach remains undisclosed, but the hackers claimed access to various crucial documents. These documents range from engineering projects and financial records to confidential contracts and internal company correspondence.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><strong>The Consequences of LockBit Ransomware Attack</strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Presently, FEAM Aero operates at nearly 52 maintenance bases globally. With more than 1500 aviation professionals servicing multiple aircraft models for major cargo &amp; commercial airlines, including DHL, Amazon, Singapore Airlines, and Air France, the potential outgrowth of this breach is a cause for noteworthy concern.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The gravity of this malware attack extends further as LockBit gave hints at exploiting the sensitive data for criminal intent. Their threats include several potential attacks on numerous FEAM Aero customers, an alarming prospect that creates an urgency for extensive cybersecurity measures.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Operating across several international airports, FEAM Aero is facing a fast-approaching challenge in reducing the consequences of this breach. Contact has been initiated with the FEAM Aero company for further clarification and alleviation efforts, awaiting an official response amid this censorious breach in aviation security.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 'Ransomware Attack', 'feam-aero-suffers-data-breach-due-to-lockbit-ransomware-attack', 'Ransomware Attack , Data Breach', 'FEAM Aero faces a data breach aftermath as it falls victim to a LockBit ransomware attack. Stay informed on cybersecurity developments to protect your organization from similar threats.', 1, '2023-11-23 09:56:38'),
(32, 'Hackers Deploying REMCOS RAT to Exploit Windows SmartScreen Zero-Day Flaws', 'hackers-deploying-remcos-rat-to-exploit-windows-smartscreen-zero-day-flaws', 1, '2101190857ttb news image1.jpg', '<p>Microsoft has issued a series of security patches as part of its Patch Tuesday initiative, addressing several vulnerabilities, including three zero-day vulnerabilities. Among these, CVE-2023-36025 stood out, impacting the Windows SmartScreen function.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This particular zero-day vulnerability, rated at 8.8 (High) in severity, was actively exploited by threat actors in real-world scenarios. Identified as a security bypass vulnerability, it necessitates user interaction for successful exploitation.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Windows SmartScreen Zero-day Flaw</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>The Windows SmartScreen Zero-day Vulnerability targets the SmartScreen feature, which typically warns users about potentially harmful websites and files. Exploiting this vulnerability enables threat actors to create specialized files or hyperlinks capable of circumventing SmartScreen&#39;s security alerts.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Notably, the vulnerability was specifically associated with a crafted Internet Shortcut File (.URL) that SmartScreen fails to validate adequately.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>An example of the exploit code is as follows:</p>\r\n\r\n<table cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"border-collapse:collapse; width:455px\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #000000; border-left:1px solid #000000; border-right:1px solid #000000; border-top:1px solid #000000; vertical-align:top; width:455px\">\r\n			<p>[InternetShortcut]</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>URL=malicious-website.com</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>IDList=</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>IconFile=\\\\\\\\192.168.1.100\\\\share\\\\icon.ico</p>\r\n\r\n			<p>IconIndex=1</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>In this instance, the URL directs to a malicious website, and the IconFile path may point to a network location under the threat actor&#39;s control. This combination allows threat actors to download malicious payloads and execute them on vulnerable systems.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img src=\"https://lh7-us.googleusercontent.com/k4nthEUK2xXNy1PsBvDK76Hylz5xofIxQm5KYHka36r4T5vsmPyB8sFbGbftu-9Z4AfA2y9ZBEcWow8fqvv8u5S6kh7u4UJk8BCgItZVpfHX9PV_Lv74J3wf9jtRz84IZAWrxcO1s34a6fwjFCUNFmI\" style=\"height:307px; width:276px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Furthermore, the malicious file&#39;s initial distribution might occur through phishing emails or compromised websites. Users who download and click on the malicious internet shortcut file inadvertently trigger the payload, providing threat actors with unauthorized access.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&#39;s important to note that a comprehensive proof of concept for this vulnerability has been published, offering detailed insights into the source code, methodology, and other pertinent information.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 'Windows SmartScreen Zero-day', 'hackers-deploying-remcos-rat-to-exploit-windows-smartscreen-zero-day-flaws', 'Windows SmartScreen, Microsoft', 'Zero-day vulnerabilities in Windows SmartScreen pose a serious security threat, allowing hackers to exploit the flaws for unauthorized access and control.', 1, '2023-11-24 04:20:58'),
(33, 'New Security Updates Introduced to Firefox 120: A Sneak Peek', 'new-security-updates-introduced-to-firefox-120-a-sneak-peek', 1, '1172404104ttb news image2.jpg', '<p>Mozilla Firefox has rolled out version 120, addressing a total of 10 vulnerabilities, including six categorized as &#39;High Severity,&#39; along with two moderate and low severity issues.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Key Highlights of Changes to Firefox 120</h2>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>The update introduces a Global Privacy Control setting.</li>\r\n	<li>Users now have the option to import data from Chromium Snap.</li>\r\n	<li>A new feature allows users to copy links without including site tracking information.</li>\r\n	<li>The Picture-in-Picture mode on Windows and Linux now supports corner snapping.</li>\r\n	<li>The release includes the addition of a new feature in the Developer Tools.</li>\r\n	<li>TLS trust anchors can now be imported.</li>\r\n	<li>Improvements have been made in private windows and the ETP-Strict privacy configuration.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h2>High Severity Flaws Addressed</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>There were several high-severity issues that were reported upon testing and are now fixed. They are:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>CVE-2023-6204</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>This vulnerability allowed for an out-of-bounds read and memory data leakage into images created on the canvas element. Reported by JSec of Hayyim Security.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>CVE-2023-6205</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The bug permitted the use of a MessagePort after it had been freed, potentially leading to an exploitable crash. Reported by Yangkang of the 360 ATA Team.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>CVE-2023-6206</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>This issue involved a black fade animation during exit from fullscreen, potentially leading to clickjacking. Reported by Hafiizh.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>CVE-2023-6207</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>A Use-after-free in ReadableByteStreamQueueEntry::Buffer was fixed. Reported by Yangkang of the 360 ATA Team.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>CVE-2023-6212</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>A memory safety bug was fixed in Firefox 120, ESR 115.5, and Thunderbird 115.5.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>CVE-2023-6213</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Firefox 120 has addressed memory safety issues, which is the flaw identified as CVE-2023-6213. Developers for Mozilla reported both of the bugs with high severity.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In addition, memory safety issues were addressed, and developers at Mozilla reported evidence of memory corruption. There&#39;s a presumption that with sufficient effort, some of these could have been exploited to run arbitrary code.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Moderate and Low Severity Issues&nbsp;</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Moderate Severity Issues that were addressed include:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>CVE-2023-6208</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Using the Selection API would copy contents into X11 primary selection.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>CVE-2023-6209</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Incorrect parsing of relative URLs starting with.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Low Severity Issues Addressed</h2>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>CVE-2023-6210</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mixed-content resources are no longer unblocked in a javascript: pop-up.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>CVE-2023-6211</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Clickjacking to load insecure pages in HTTPS-only mode.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For those interested, Firefox 120 is available for download on the Mozilla website, compatible with Windows, macOS, and Linux.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 'Mozilla Firefox 120', 'new-security-updates-introduced-to-firefox-120-a-sneak-peek', 'Mozilla Firefox 120 , CVE-2023', 'Experience enhanced browsing with Mozilla Firefox 120. Enjoy improved speed, privacy features, and a seamless user interface.', 1, '2023-11-24 10:35:26');
